The unity pact between President Uhuru Kenyatta and Nasa leader Raila Odinga has put to an end the long electioneering period and set the country on the development path, two Jubilee MPs have said. Gichugu MP Robert Gichimu said there would be no problem if Raila was given a slot in government as long as he recognizes Uhuru as the duly elected president. He said the powers of the president should however remain intact in the event that there will be need to amend the Constitution to accommodate the opposition leader in government. Read: Gideon Moi: By meeting Raila, Uhuru proved he's ready to walk the unity talk His sentiments were echoed by Kirinyaga senator Charles Kibiru who said it is time Raila and the entire NASA coalition recognized the Jubilee government and Uhuru as the duly elected president. "It is now time for Raila to recognise President Uhuru
Kenyatta and forget about being the peoples' president," Kibiru said. The two legislators spoke on Saturday at Kiamutugu Secondary School in Gichugu constituency. Uhuru and Raila came together on Friday in what they said was aimed at uniting the country following a protracted electioneering period highlighted by two elections. Related: Mudavadi trashes Uhuru-Raila pact, says not reflecting the will of Kenyans Even after the meeting at Harambee House, Nairobi, Raila is yet to formally recognize Uhuru's presidency. At one point, Raila and his supporters led by economist David Ndii were pushing for session of Nasa affiliate counties using the People's Assemblies. The motion, which has since been passed by at least 16 counties was part of the strategies employed by Raila and his team to agitate for what they termed electoral justice. Also read: Raila took calculated risk to avert bloodshed - Salim Lone  Click here for the latest political news 